{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-05-03-029Z","slug":"your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance","locale":"fr","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:05:34.787Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/fr/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-05-03-029Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"710eef136b3fb20edb779995cdd3e6132250ff49ebbe95c2159902711bea426c","outputHash":"cb5aef328d9adc828d344d26805cf3b970d606026049f706029c3fc3288c37f5","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary:**  \nThe article argues against the misconception that foreign keys (FKs) are inherently slow and should be removed for scalability. It critiques the \"fast vs. correct\" false dichotomy, emphasizing that FKs enforce data integrity at the cost of write performance, but their removal often leads to worse long-term issues like orphaned records and corrupted billing systems. The author uses car safety analogies (e.g., seatbelts add weight but prioritize safety) to frame FKs as trade-offs between failure modes, not just speed. Key examples include a weather monitoring system where static data (e.g., US states) doesn’t need FKs, while mutable data (e.g., weather stations) might, and a denormalized `sensor_log` table using JSONB for high-throughput writes. The article also warns against rigid normalization, advocating for snapshot data storage (e.g., embedding product details in orders) to avoid excessive joins.  \n\n**Core thesis","totalInputTokens":10462,"totalOutputTokens":10296,"totalCacheReadTokens":1536,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":24155,"totalCostUsd":0.003308,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32